Ohcejoga dieđa- ja dáiddadállu prošeakta jođus

Ealáhuslávdegotti válljii čoahkkimisttis 22. guovvamánu Ohcejoga dieđa- ja dáiddadálu prošeavtta koordináhtorin Marja-Riitta Lukkari. Dieđa- ja dáiddadállu prošeakta lea dovddus maid Áilegas-instituhtta namain. Álgga boaris visttiid ordnemis dieđa ja dáidaga várás vulggii johtui moanaid jagiid dassái Sámi allaskuvlla professor Vuokko Hirvonenis ja allaskuvlla lektoris Pigga Lauhamaas.

Ohcejoga gielda lea ožžon ruhtadeami Lappi birasguovddážis Ohcejoga Dieđa- ja dáiddadálu ordnenbargui sihke Lappi leanaráđđehusas Ohcejoga Dieđa- ja dáiddadálu álggahanbargui. Prošeavtta ulbmilin lea álggahit boares skuvlla giddodagas, mii divoduvvo, Ohcejoga dieda- ja dáiddadállodoaimmaid ja ovddidit doaimma nu ahte dat doarju guovllu ealáhuseallima, kulturfálaldagaid ja innovašuvnnaid šaddama.

Prošeavttas ee. biddjojuvvo áiggi dássái giddodaga várás dahkkon latnjaplána, ovddiduvvo dieđa- ja dáiddadálu doaibmamálle, ožžojuvvo áigái innovatiivalaš doaibmabiras doaibmiide, čatnasahttojit doaibmit, dorvvastuvvo doaimma joatkevašvuohta ja ordnejuvvojit boares skuvlagiddodagat. Prošeaktakoordináhtora virggi ohce njealjis.

Ášševalmmaštalli Hanna-Leena Talvensaari mielde ohcamušaid ja jearahallamiid vuođul Marja-Riitta Lukkari devddii buoremusat gáibiduvvon eavttuid, sus lea ohcciin buoremus hárjánupmi dán sullasaš bargguin (ee. sámedikki kulturguovddášprojeakta) ja sus lea buoremus čanasjoavkodovdamuš ovddit bargohárjánumi vuođul. Lassin sus jearahallama vuođul lea projeavttas dárbbašlaš oaidnu guovllu ovdánahttimis ja son lea innovatiivalaš, sus leat oktasašbargonávccat ja son lea iešdoaimmalaš.

Ealáhuslávdegotti nammadii gieldda iežas ovddasteaddji prošeavtta stivrenjovkui. Stivrenjoavkku bargun lea ee. gohcit ja bearráigeahččat prošeavtta ovdáneami. Stivrenjoavku ii daga juridihkalaš mearrádusaid. Ealáhuslávdegoddi válljii ovddasteaddjin projeavtta stivrenjovkui Vieno Länsmana ja várrelahttun Tapani Tapiola.

I vote for the Odyssey given Madmom"s family and dog iaccifieptsons. Gnomica had one that worked great for all her needs hauling kids, lumber, dogs (she has one of mine ) until one of her boyfriends wrecked it. As to where you find the deals, I don"t know. My dad used to get his cars from the local Chrysler dealer who was a good friend and would keep an eye on all the trade-ins that came in and give him a call when he got a jewel. Unfortunately, the owner retired and sold the dealership to a conglomerate, so now my dad has the same car problems as Madmom. So he keeps driving the old clunkers, just like Mr. gnome and I do. Although we have now switched cars, because mine costs less to operate on all the long trips to Houston that he takes every week. It also looks a lot better, being a Volvo, while I drive his Suburban which has some very nice dents in it. Mr. Gnome is not known for his spatial reasoning. They both have over 100,000 miles on them.I need to get to work. I have got six hours to clean the house. Mr. Gnome is bringing S-I-L in tonight. I think the dogs are still worn out from the hike last night. they"ve been snoozing all day.

The best advice that you can reiceve , is to practice, practice practice. I don"t mean for you to go to the driving range and bash balls as that will do you little good . You will have to have a plan. Work your short irons first ,then your middle irons working your way down to your long irons. Then you will be ready to hit you shortest woods first working your way to your longest, all the while aiming at a target. Since you said that you are having trouble with your short game , then you should practice it more than the other clubs. On the range find the yardage marker that is equal in length to say your longest wedge ,100 yards and shorter and just hit shots at the marker, concentrating on getting as close as possible, then move on to the next shortest wedge and once again find the yardage marker that corresponds with it , doing the same with it and so on ( I have four wedges ). Next move to the practice putting green and practice chipping and pitching from around the green. Once you have the balls on the green , you might as well practice putting as you can never get enough putting. Good luck Was this answer helpful?
